Author::::RichM49
DateTime::::2016-03-11T16:14:40Z
Much of the problem with Mathematics is that it is expressed in a very formal language with a strict grammatical structure and precise application of logic. Unfortunately for most people their first encounter with grammar (not to be confused with spelling) and logic is via English. I believe a sound understanding of the grammatical underpinning of English ( or any other langauge) is key to developing an understanding of mathematics and the language of mathematics but the teaching of this is weak. Perhaps the reason that other countries such as China are ahead of us in Mathematics teaching lies in the structure of their language. We can distinquish between English in a social context and Academic English which can be taught formally following the principles of Applied Linquistics as was tried in Solihull some years ago.



