Author::::ID8349490
DateTime::::2016-03-11T10:31:13Z
Another day,another curmudgeonly article by Simon Jenkins. Where to begin?Firstly,i will declare my interest-i have a Maths degree,and i teach the subject to students,but,even if i didn't teach it,i would love it for the fact that it enriches my life in immeasurable ways.Jenkins says he studied "higher maths from calculus to number theory",to study number theory,you would have to do a maths degree,since even physicists-being the nearest thing there is to a mathematician-are not taught this branch of the subject. To have then forgotten it all would seem unlikely to say the least,but still......A quote from Charles Darwin:-"I have deeply regretted that i did not proceed far enough at least to understand something of the great leading principles of mathematics;for those thus endowed seem to have an extra sense". This is true-in all the sciences,not just my speciality of astrophysics,i feel like i have a way in,because i can speak the language that the world is written in (Galileo). I agree with him that Paulos' Innumeracy is an excellent book,although his comment about statisticians is again ignorant and unfair-statisticians do not try to con with statistics,quite the opposite in fact. People who use statistics-politicians and journalists mainly-try to do that. In fairness,this is often out of ignorance,rather than malice,but the end result-chaos ans confusion-is unfortunately the same. Statistics done right tells us what is actually happening out there in the world,rather than what we think may be-this last being,usually, a function of our ignorance and our prejudice. Florence Nightingale's quote:"To understand God's thoughts,one must study Statistics,for these are the measure of his purpose" needs no religious belief,and works just as well in an entirely secular context.Mathematics,statistics and science are our candles in the dark against ignorance and superstition,and they are needed more than ever these days it seems. I cannot for the life of me see how a more mathematically and scientifically literate population would be a bad thing. I accept,however,the thesis that it should be taught in context and not just for its own sake,as most people who love maths come to it through applications;they learn to love it for itself (if they do) later on. So,i reject Hardy's view-lovers of mathematics have nothing to apologise for.It is also not true that every worthwhile application involves higher maths (calculus principally,but not exclusively). Many everyday phenomena in the world around us can be explained with simple ideas. For example,calculating the distance to the horizon from the top of a hill (Pythagoras),why you can see further in heavy rain than misty rain (simple geometry),measuring the width of a river,or the height of a tall object (trigonometry),scaling problems of all sorts,eg,why is an elephant not a scaled-up mouse (the square-cube law),and so on and so on. The list is nearly endless. (I recognise the fact that "interesting" is in the mind's eye of the beholder,and so varies from person to person).I agree that science as taught in schools has broadened out to include more contemporary,and hopefully interesting,topics,but,and it is a big but,the basics of physics must still be taught,or there is no point-"There are two kinds of science:physics and stamp-collecting",as Rutherford once famously remarked.On financial mathematics:-the Black-Scholes equation and its variants were not to blame for the financial crisis. It was people using them incorrectly that did that. Mathematical models are wonderful things,but only where they apply-they must not be used outside their domain of influence,and this is often done by people who don't understand what they are doing. All models are wrong,but many are useful.On the recommending of books:anything by Paulos is good,and for those who wish to understand more about science in general,i would highly recommend Gregory Derry's What Science is,and how it works. It contains very little maths to put off a general reader,in case that should be a problem. I could add a great deal more,but this post has been quite long enough already!



